    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 0.76,
      "end": 2.46,
      "text": "This is a Libra Box Recording.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 3.2,
      "end": 5.64,
      "text": "All Libra Box Recordings are in the public domain.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 6.6,
      "end": 11.28,
      "text": "For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibraBox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 11.88,
      "end": 17.0,
      "text": "Recorded by Kim Stone of Pirling on the Dark Side in Denver, Colorado, USA.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 18.22,
      "end": 20.78,
      "text": "ESOP's Fables, the Oak and the Reeds.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 21.72,
      "end": 27.1,
      "text": "An oak that grew on the bank of a river was uprooted by a severe gale of wind and thrown",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 27.1,
      "end": 28.18,
      "text": "across the stream.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 28.82,
      "end": 32.62,
      "text": "It fell among some reeds growing by the water and said to them,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 33.22,
      "end": 39.52,
      "text": "How is it that you who are so frail and slender have managed to weather the storm whereas I,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 39.88,
      "end": 44.04,
      "text": "with all my strength, have been torn up by the roots and hurled into the river?",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 44.78,
      "end": 50.5,
      "text": "You were stubborn came the reply and fought against the storm which proves stronger than you.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-011",
      "start": 51.24,
      "end": 56.86,
      "text": "But we bow and yield to every breeze and thus the gale passed harmlessly over our heads.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-012",
      "start": 56.86,
      "end": 59.96,
      "text": "End of the oak and the reeds.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
